[src:dom-events/api-event] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:dom-events/api-event] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:dom-events/api-event] The **`Event`** interface represents an event which takes place on an `EventTarget`.
[src:dom-events/api-event] An event can be triggered by the user action e.g., clicking the mouse button or tapping the keyboard, or generated by APIs to represent the progress of an asynchronous task.
[src:dom-events/api-event] It can also be triggered programmatically, such as by calling the `HTMLElement.click()` method of an element, or by defining the event, then sending it to a specified target using `EventTarget.dispatchEvent()`.
[src:dom-events/api-event] There are many types of events, some of which use other interfaces based on the main `Event` interface.
[src:dom-events/api-event] `Event` itself contains the properties and methods which are common to all events.
[src:dom-events/api-event] Many DOM elements can be set up to accept (or "listen" for) these events, and execute code in response to process (or "handle") them.
[src:dom-events/api-event] Event-handlers are usually connected (or "attached") to various HTML elements (such as `<button>`, `<div>`, `<span>`, etc.) using `EventTarget.addEventListener()`, and this generally replaces using the old HTML event handler attributes.
[src:dom-events/api-event] Further, when properly added, such handlers can also be disconnected if needed using `removeEventListener()`.
[src:dom-events/api-event] Below is a list of interfaces which are based on the main `Event` interface, with links to their respective documentation in the MDN API reference.
[src:dom-events/api-event] Note that all event interfaces have names which end in "Event".
