[src:dom-events/scripting-events] It's just a copy of the simple random color example we've played with already.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] Some events, such as `click`, are available on nearly any element.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] Others are more specific and only useful in certain situations: for example, the `play` event is only available on elements that have play functionality, such as `<video>`.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] If you've added an event listener using `addEventListener()`, you can remove it again if desired.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] The most common way to do this is by using the `removeEventListener()` method.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] For simple, small programs, cleaning up old, unused event handlers isn't necessary, but for larger, more complex programs, it can improve efficiency.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] Also, the ability to remove event handlers allows you to have the same button performing different actions in different circumstances: all you have to do is add or remove handlers.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] Both functions would now run when the element is clicked.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] We recommend that you use `addEventListener()` to register event handlers.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] It's the most powerful method and scales best with more complex programs.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] However, there are two other ways of registering event handlers that you might see: *event handler properties* and *inline event handlers*.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] Objects (such as buttons) that can fire events also usually have properties whose name is `on` followed by the name of an event.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] For example, elements have a property `onclick`.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] This is called an **event handler property**.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] To listen for the event, you can assign the handler function to the property.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] Event handler properties have disadvantages compared to `addEventListener()`.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] One of the most significant is that you can't add more than one listener for a single event.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] The earliest method of registering event handlers found on the Web involved *event handler HTML attributes* (or *inline event handlers*) like the one shown above — the attribute value contains the JavaScript code you want to run when the event occurs.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] You can find HTML attribute equivalents for many of the event handler properties; however, you shouldn't use these — they are considered bad practice.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] It might seem easy to use an event handler attribute if you are doing something really quick, but they quickly become unmanageable and inefficient.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] For a start, it is not a good idea to mix up your HTML and your JavaScript, as it becomes hard to read.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] Keeping your JavaScript separate is a good practice, and if it is in a separate file you can apply it to multiple HTML documents.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] Even in a single file, inline event handlers are not a good idea.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] One button is OK, but what if you had 100 buttons?
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] You'd have to add 100 attributes to the file; it would quickly turn into a maintenance nightmare.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] Finally, many common server configurations will disallow inline JavaScript, as a security measure.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] Sometimes, inside an event handler function, you'll see a parameter specified with a name such as `event`, `evt`, or `e`.
