[src:dom-events/scripting-events] Sometimes, you'll come across a situation where you want to prevent an event from doing what it does by default.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] The most common example is that of a web form, for example, a custom registration form.
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] When you fill in the details and click the submit button, the natural behavior is for the data to be submitted to a specified page on the server for processing, and the browser to be redirected to a "success message" page of some kind (or the same page, if another is not specified).
[src:dom-events/scripting-events] The trouble comes when the user has not submitted the data correctly — as a developer, you want to prevent the submission to the server and give an error message saying what's wrong and what needs to be done to put things right.
